<H3> <TI>   Foreign Observers To Arrive in Hebron Early May </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Observers To Arrive in Hebron Early May </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1804094994 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1146 GMT 17 
Apr 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1804094994 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Mideast: Observers in Hebron By May, </F>
Italian Diplomats Say"] 
  [Excerpt] (ANSA) Tel Aviv, April 17 -- Barring unforeseen 
obstacles, international peacekeepers from Norway, Denmark, and 
Italy may begin deployment in the West Bank city of Hebron by 
the end of April or the beginning of May, according to Italian 
diplomats here. Delegations from the three countries, which in 
March proposed sending observers under a so-called Temporary 
International Presence in Hebron [TIPH], are continuing 
preparations to send 90 Norwegians, 35 Danes and 35 Italians in 
the Israeli-occupied city where tensions have been escalating 
ever since a Jewish settler opened fire on dozens of 
Palestinians as they prayed in the Hebron mosque on February 25. 
  The diplomats told ANSA that the two high-ranking 
Carabinieri 
police officers and Rome Foreign Ministry officials who visited 
Hebron on April 11 have been shuttling between the Palestinian 
city, Tel Aviv and Jerusalem with their counterparts from Norway 
and Denmark in an effort to resolve a series of practical 
problems, such as deciding where the observers will reside. 
  The TIPH members will be carrying only light weapons for 
self-defense and hope to ease tensions between Israeli settlers 
and the armed forces and local residents. 
  A memorandum officially getting the mission under way should 
be signed in Copenhagen some time at the end of next week and 
unless new obstacles are raised, deployment may begin as early 
as the end of the month, the diplomats said. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

