<F P=101> Israel </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows Netanyahu Favored Over Rabin in 2-Way Race </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll Shows Netanyahu Favored Over Rabin in 2-Way Race </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1504100994 Jerusalem THE JERUSALEM POST in English 15 Apr 
94 p A2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> TA1504100994 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem THE JERUSALEM POST </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] If the election for prime minister were held today, 
Likud leader Binyamin Netanyahu would get 44 percent of the vote 
to Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin's 38 percent, according to 
Gallup-Israel. Eighteen percent of the respondents were 
undecided. 
  This is the first time since Netanyahu's election as Likud 
party chairman that he topped Rabin. However, in a three-way 
race, in which Tzomet leader Refa'el Eytan would also be a 
candidate, Rabin would receive the largest number of votes -- 34 
percent, to Netanyahu's 29 percent and Eytan's 18 percent. 
  The poll, taken in regular intervals since January, shows a 
steady decline in Rabin's popularity, from a peak of 44 percent 
in a three-way race on January 31st, and 49 percent against 
Netanyahu's 34 percent in a two-way match on that date. 
  The sample is country-wide, representing 500-600 Hebrew 
speaking adults. The margin of error is 4 percent. 

</TEXT>

