<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Israel's Shohat on `Possible Crisis,' `New Demands' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Israel's Shohat on `Possible Crisis,' `New Demands' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2104161094 Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew 1400 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2104161094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv IDF Radio </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by special correspondent in Paris Eldad Beck] </F>
  [Text] Until midday today, the Israeli delegates spoke of 
serious difficulties the economic talks were encountering, but 
now Finance Minister Avraham Shohat, who heads the delegation, 
speaks of a possible crisis. According to Shohat, the 
Palestinians presented new demands during this week's talks. He 
has informed chief Palestinian delegate Abu-al-'Ala' [Ahmad 
Quray'] that these demands are unacceptable and that they are 
liable to result in a very serious crisis in the economic 
negotiations. 
  Shohat asserted that the Palestinians want to expand the 
list 
of products whose customs Israel has consented to reduce. The 
original list has been doubled by the Palestinians, and it now 
includes goods to be imported from countries which do not trade 
with Israel, namely Arab countries. We cannot agree to such 
things, Shohat said; the import regime must be uniform. 
  There is no telling whether the Israeli verbal escalation 
was 
designed to produce psychological pressure on the Palestinians. 
In any event, the negotiations will continue through the night. 
Tomorrow the finance minister will return to Israel to attend 
the 24 April cabinet meeting. He will fly back to Paris 
straight after the meeting. The Israeli delegation will stay in 
the French capital to continue the talks with the Palestinians. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

