<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin Holds Consultations on `Final Stage' of Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rabin Holds Consultations on `Final Stage' of Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2204112394 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in English 1100 GMT 22 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2204112394 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Prime Minister Rabin this morning held 
consultations on what is thought to be the final stage of the 
peace talks. Israeli and PLO leaders have said the talks may be 
completed next week, though this was not certain. If they are, 
the agreement could be signed in Cairo by Rabin and Yasir 
'Arafat in the first week of May. Jack Katzenell reports: 
  [Begin Katzenell recording] Taking part at this morning's 
meeting at the Defense Ministry in Tel Aviv were Prime Minister 
Rabin, Justice Minister David Liba'i, Environment Minister Yosi 
Sarid, and the Israeli negotiators at the Cairo talks, headed by 
Major General Amnon Shahaq. It emerged that the civilian issues 
being negotiated with the PLO were almost completely settled. 
These have to do with the transfer of power in Gaza and Jericho 
from the Israeli civilian administration to the Palestinian 
authority and many other matters. But certain issues have not 
yet been settled -- for example, the number of Palestinian 
prisoners to be released. The criteria for their release were 
discussed at this morning's meeting. They will not include 
those who have murdered Israelis, and Israel insists that they 
should not include people who committed terrorist acts after 13 
September, when the Oslo agreement was signed. The most 
difficult issue not yet settled is that of jurisdiction. 
  Minister Yosi Sarid said after this morning's meeting that 
no 
Israeli will be tried in a Palestinian court. If an Israeli is 
accused of committing an offense in Gaza or Jericho, he will be 
tried in Israel, Sarid said. If this or any other issue is not 
settled by next week, the Israeli and PLO liaison committee will 
meet in Cairo under the joint chairmanship of Foreign Minister 
Peres and Abu-Mazin [Mahmud 'Abbas]. [passage omitted] [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

