<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Asks Iraqi Opposition To Cease Activities </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Asks Iraqi Opposition To Cease Activities </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2104153694 Amman AKHBAR AL-USBU' in Arabic 21 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> JN2104153694 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AKHBAR AL-USBU' </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Jordanian security authorities have reinforced 
security precautions to protect Iraqi opposition figures 
residing in Amman after the assassination of Shaykh Talib 
al-Suhayl in Beirut. 
  The Jordanian Interior Ministry asked the Iraqi opposition 
in 
Jordan to stop its political and media activities against Iraq 
and to adhere to observed regulations and laws. The Jordanian 
Interior Ministry also decided not to renew the residency of any 
Iraqi opposition after it expires. This is in order to limit 
the activities of the Iraqi opposition and to prevent any future 
tension between Jordanian authorities and the opposition if it 
violates the red lines set by the Jordanian Government. 
  It was learned that although the Jordanian Government 
allowed 
a number of Iraqi opposition members to live in Amman, this does 
not mean they are allowed to practice political and media 
activities. This is especially true because Jordan is a 
democratic country and cannot prevent any Arab citizen from 
living in it as a long as he adheres to the regulations and 
laws. Despite the fact that the opposition is carrying out 
some simple social activities and is sending some faxes here and 
there, this is not the same as allowing the Iraqi opposition to 
work. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

