<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Task Force Agrees on Joint Projects With Nepal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Task Force Agrees on Joint Projects With Nepal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1604165294 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 1530 
GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1604165294 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] India and Nepal have decided to accord priority to 
the completion of several road projects. The meeting of the 
India-Nepalese high level task force in New Delhi today also 
decided to expand the Bir Hospital in Nepal. The projects to be 
completed on a priority bases are 17 bridges on the 
Kolhapur-Badrapur Road and the Chatara-Birpur Road. The task 
force stressed the early completion of project reports on the 
Burhi Gandak and the Panchesh projects. The progress in these 
sectors will be reviewed by a secretary-level meeting next 
month. The task force also considered several new project 
proposals including the India-Nepal broad-gauge railway link 
from Raxaul to a point in Nepal. It expressed satisfaction over 
the progress of Indian-aided projects in Nepal. The high-level 
task force is headed by the principal secretary to the prime 
minister, Mr. A.N. Varma, and the chief secretary to the 
Government of Nepal, Mr. M.P. Gorkhali. 
  The Nepalese delegation today called on the external affairs 
minister, Mr. Dinesh Singh, and the minister of state, Mr. R.L. 
Bhatia. Mr. Dinesh Singh said there is significant potential 
for bilateral cooperation in the development of water resources. 
He lauded the work of the task force in ensuring successful 
completion of Indian-aided projects in Nepal. 
  The prime minister, Mr. Narasimha Rao, has said India and 
Nepal should expedite all the agreed projects which symbolize 
the excellent cooperation between the two countries. Talking to 
members of the Nepalese delegation on the India-Nepal high-level 
task force, who called on him in New Delhi today, Mr. Rao 
described the relations between the two countries as close and 
friendly. 

</TEXT>

