<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Denies YSP Claims; Army Attacks Kidnappers' Site </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Denies YSP Claims; Army Attacks Kidnappers' Site </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2204183094 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 1700 GMT 22 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2204183094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A northern Yemeni official denied in Sanaa today 
that military reinforcements were sent to the northern 
al-'Amaliqah brigade which is stationed in the south, saying 
planes are transporting only food and medicine to troops 
stationed in the area. 
  The Yemeni official, who asked not to be named, said 
northern 
planes are now assuming this task because supplies for the al- 
'Amaliqah Brigade were cut off by the southern 20th Brigade in 
Mukayris, the point from which these items reached the Abyan 
area north of Aden where the al-'Amaliqah brigade is stationed. 
  The north Yemeni official was responding to a Yemeni 
Socialist Party [YSP] statement issued last night accusing 
northern forces of sending reinforcements to the al-'Amaliqah 
Brigade in the south of the country. The YSP statement said 
seven helicopters carrying arms, military equipment, and troops 
landed at the al-'Amaliqah brigade's military camp and that at 
least 10 tanks and missile carriers were brought to beef up 
northern army positions in the central part of the previous 
border between the two parts of Yemen. 
  On another level, the Yemeni Army today attacked a site 
where 
the Jahm tribal elements have been detaining for one month three 
Netherlands nationals in a mountainous area, 200 km east of 
Sanaa. The Ma'rib district governor left for the site in an 
attempt to release the three captives, who had been working in a 
project to supply the capital with water. The kidnappers are 
trying to force the Yemeni authorities to employ members of the 
Jahm tribe in oil companies and the army. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

