<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Heavy Casualties Reported in Kabul Fighting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Heavy Casualties Reported in Kabul Fighting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2304124594 Hong Kong AFP in English 1213 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK2304124594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kabul, April 23 (AFP) -- At least 158 people were 
injured in an overnight battle that erupted in Kabul between 
rival forces fighting for and against President Borhanoddin 
Rabbani, officials said here Saturday [23 April]. 
  Troops exchanged artillery and heavy weapons fire during the 
clash, but government troops said they had "repulsed" renegade 
fighters of Afghan Prime Minister Golboddin Hektmatyar. 
  They also claimed that "heavy casualties" were inflicted on 
the troops of Hekmatyar and Uzbek fighters of militia warlord 
'Abdol Rashid Dostam, the premier's main battle ally. 
  "The attack started at 7 p.m. (1430 GMT) and reached its 
peak 
at 10 p.m. lasting till midnight," a government soldier told AFP 
in the scarred Microrayan housing estate, situated near the 
former diplomatic enclave of Wazir Akbar Khan. 
  Rabbani's troops on Kabul's eastern front said troops of 
Hekmatyar and Dostam's Uzbek warriors attacked them at several 
points. 
  Hekmatyar's Shiite ally, the Hezb-i-Wahdat faction, also 
joined the battle, engaging Rabbani's troops at the city's 
south, the government troops said. 
  Reports of deaths from the clash were not immediately 
available but the Jamhurriat hospital here said three civilians 
died of their injuries while a 10-year-old boy with a bullet 
wound in the chest was in a critical condition. 
  During Friday's fighting a phosphorus shell slammed into the 
International Committee of the Red Cross complex but did not 
explode, but it ignited when Western demining experts were 
extracting the ordnance, relief workers said. 
  A few civilians still residing in the remaining Microrayan 
apartment estate said they spent the night in makeshift shelters 
or in the basements as shells whined overhead and bullets 
scoured homes. 
  Residents in one Microrayon block said only four of the 60 
apartments there were occupied as most residents had fled since 
rival forces turned the residential district into a regular 
battle ground four months ago. 
  Troops of Dostam, Hekmatyar and Rabbani are battling since 
January to take control of Microrayon, a sprawling residential 
enclave built by the former Soviet Union for its Red Army 
officers after it invaded Afghanistan in 1979. 
  Angry Microrayon residents came out of their homes to hurl 
curses at the United Nations, Western nations and the Afghan 
mojahedin for their woes as a lull in the battle set in 
Saturday, witnesses said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

