<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Ministry Says PRC Border Situation `Normal' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Ministry Says PRC Border Situation `Normal' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2504091494 Hong Kong AFP in English 0855 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK2504091494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] New Delhi, April 25 (AFP) -- India has not observed 
large-scale movements of Chinese troops into Tibet and the 
situation along the Indo-Tibetan frontier is "absolutely 
normal," a defense ministry spokesman said here Monday [25 
April]. 
  The Indian spokesman dismissed assertions by Tibetan sources 
that up to 30,000 Chinese soldiers had moved into Tibet during 
the past three weeks and that many of them had deployed along 
Tibet's border with India. 
  "We don't have any information like that," the defence 
ministry spokesman said. "The situation (along the border) is 
absolutely normal." 
  Noting that Indian and Chinese officials held a round of 
talks on border questions in Beijing last week, the spokesman 
said "this is the time when these troop numbers should go down. 
  "And we are making quite smooth progress in that regard," he 
added. 
  The London-based Tibet Information Network, citing sources 
in 
the Tibetan government-in-exile based in the Indian hill town of 
Dharamsala, reported Sunday that China had sent some 30,000 
additional troops into Tibet. 
  "The troop movements, the largest reported from the area 
since martial law was lifted from the Tibetan capital in 1990, 
appear to be concentrated around the Tibetan border with India," 
the Network said. 
  Tibetan sources here contacted by AFP said three divisions 
of 
People's Liberation Army soldiers had entered Tibet in the last 
week of March and first week of April. 
  They said many of the troops had moved to the Tibetan region 
bordering the far northeastern Indian states of Arunachal 
Pradesh and Sikkim. 
  The Dalai Lama, the Tibetan spiritual leader, has been based 
in India with some 100,000 of his followers since fleeing his 
homeland following a failed anti-Chinese uprising in 1959. 
  Indian and Chinese officials meet regularly to discuss ways 
to keep the peace on the border, subject of a dispute that took 
the two countries to a brief but bitter war in 1962. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-13766 </DOCNO>
