<H3> <TI>   Bhutto's Aide Elected Leader of NWFP Assembly </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bhutto's Aide Elected Leader of NWFP Assembly </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2404085694 Islamabad Radio Pakistan Overseas Service in 
English 0800 GMT 24 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2404085694 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad Radio Pakistan Overseas Service </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The NWFP [Northwest Frontier Province] Assembly held 
its session in Peshawar this morning with Mr. Abdul Akbar Khan 
in the chair as presiding officer. The house elected Mr. Aftab 
Ahmed Khan Sherpao as leader of the house. He secured 42 votes 
and none voting against. Speaking after his election as leaders 
of the house, Mr. Aftab Ahmed Khan Sherpao thanked the assembly 
members for reposing confidence in him. He invited the 
opposition members for cooperation with the ruling alliance for 
smooth running of the business of the assembly. Earlier, the 
presiding officer, Mr. Abdul Akbar Khan, read out the governor's 
order asking the former leader of the house to prove his 
majority. 
  Mr. Akbar Hussain Shah in a resolution proposed that Mr. 
Sabir Shah should prove his majority, while Shahad Mohammad Khan 
seconded. (?As the) former leader of the house and members of 
the treasury benches had abstained from the proceedings, Pir 
Sabir Shah was declared unsuccessful in proving his majority. 
Later, the name of Mr. Aftab Ahmed Khan Sherpao was proposed in 
four identical resolutions for leadership of the house. He 
succeeded in obtaining 42 votes and was declared elected 
unopposed leader of the house. 
  The session was later prorogued. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-13774 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes079_v_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-079 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Pakistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bhutto Defends Election </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bhutto Defends Election </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2404145294 Islamabad PTV Television Network in English 
1400 GMT 24 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2404145294 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad PTV Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The National Assembly today began discussion on the 
political developments in the NWFP [Northwest Frontier Province] 
suspending all other business on the agenda. The motion to this 
effect was moved by the law minister, Syed Iqbal Haider. 
Initiating the debate, the leader of the opposition, Mr. Nawaz 
Sharif, was critical of the government's action and announced 
that the opposition will boycott the proceedings of the house 
till the measures taken in the NWFP are withdrawn and a special 
committee of the house headed by an opposition member is set up 
to investigate into the Mehran Bank scandal. He then led a 
walkout by the members of the opposition. 
  Taking part in the debate, the law minister, Syed Iqbal 
Haider, explained in detail the circumstance that led to the 
present situation in the NWFP. He said steps taken in the 
provinces have been necessitated to protect and strengthen the 
democratic process, rule of law, and the Constitution. The 
basic issue in the NWFP is who enjoys majority. Only the 
majority has the right to rule the province. The law minister 
said the PDF [People's Democratic Front] emerged as the largest 
parliamentary alliance in the NWFP assembly following the 
October 1993 elections. [Former NWFP Chief Minister] Pir Sabir 
Shah, the law minister pointed out, formed the government in the 
province by purchase of loyalties, but could not satisfy the 
members who supported him. The PDF and independent members 
moved a vote of no-confidence against the chief minister in 
February when he lost the confidence of the majority. The law 
minister said tabling of the no-confidence motion was a 
constitutional step, but Mr. Sabir Shah did not face the motion 
in a democratic and constitutional manner. Syed Iqbal Haider 
said the order of the governor asking the chief minister to 
obtain a vote of confidence was perfectly within the ambit of 
the Constitution. It should have been implemented in a 
democratic way. 
  The prime minister, Ms. Benazir Bhutto, has said with the 
election of the new leaders of the house in the NWFP assembly, 
sense of stability has surfaced in Pakistan's politics. The new 
leader of the house was elected following the delivery of 
verdict on the same issue by the Supreme Court and, therefore, 
the process contains no ambiguity, she said, adding the process 
has paved the way for strengthening democratic institutions and 
bringing about stability in the country. Talking to newsmen in 
Islamabad today, the prime minister said the opposition has 
reacted to the development in the NWFP by walking out from the 
provincial assembly. She said this is one of the methods of 
registering protests and it is the right of the opposition to 
protest, but we feel the rule of majorities is an important 
principle in parliamentary form of government. 
  When her attention was drawn toward the opposition's demand 
for constituting a house committee on the affairs of Mehran Bank 
with its chairman from the opposition benches, the prime 
minister said the nation has witnessed massive loot from Taj 
Company, investment companies, cooperatives, corporations, and 
Mehran Bank scandal. She said we are not dealing with the 
matter on individual basis. We have authorized the State bank 
to plug all financial irregularities whether they are committed 
by politicians or by other citizens. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

