<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fatah, Hamas Reach Cease-Fire Agreement in Gaza </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fatah, Hamas Reach Cease-Fire Agreement in Gaza </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Fatah Source on `Political Agreement' </H4>

<F P=102> NC2304143294 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1305 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2304143294 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tunis, 23 Apr (MENA)--A prominent Palestinian source 
from Fatah, the biggest faction within the PLO, has stated that 
the agreement announced yesterday between Fatah and Hamas 
[Islamic Resistance Movement] is a "political agreement" that 
seeks to work out a specific formula for Hamas to participate in 
institutions of the future Palestinian national authority. The 
source described it as "more than just an agreement on 
cease-fire and bilateral differences." 
  The source, who took part in the recent round of 
negotiations 
with Hamas leaders in Gaza, added that Hamas had submitted 
proposals for participation in the Palestinian national 
institutions, including the Palestinian police. He pointed out 
that Palestinian president Yasir 'Arafat welcomed Hamas' offer 
and willingness to join the national authority, despite its 
earlier opposition to the Palestinian-Israeli Declaration of 
Principles. He noted that 'Arafat had accepted in principle the 
proposals made by Hamas in Gaza. The proposals were also 
approved by Musa Abu-Marzuq, head of the movement's [not further 
specified] political bureau. 
  The source stressed that 'Arafat will soon meet Hamas 
leaders 
in an Arab capital, probably Amman, to work out a final 
agreement on Hamas' participation in the Palestinian national 
authority. 'Arafat, the source added, is convinced that Hamas' 
new position represents a practical stand on the 
Palestinian-Israeli Declaration of Principles. It shows Hamas' 
desire not to be isolated from the future Palestinian national 
authority's institutions, particularly since other Palestinian 
factions, such as the George Habash-led Palestinian Front for 
the Liberation of Palestine, have expressed a desire to join 
them. 
  The same source said that during in its meeting in Tunis 
under 'Arafat yesterday, Fatah's Central Committee endorsed the 
agreement with Hamas. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-13795 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes079dd_94008" </HT>


