<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hamas Notes 2700 Palestinians Arrested in 2 Weeks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hamas Notes 2700 Palestinians Arrested in 2 Weeks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2304195294 Paris AFP in English 1743 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2304195294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Damascus, April 23 (AFP) -- The Islamic Resistance 
Movement Hamas said Saturday [23 April] the Israeli army 
arrested more than 2,700 Palestinians in the last two weeks, but 
added its militants would still continue to attack Israelis. 
  These arrests "which affect all those suspected of links to 
Hamas will not prevent more operations by the (armed wing) 
'Izz-al-Din al-Qassam nor the popular resistance" against 
Israeli occupation, Hamas said in a statement to AFP here. 
  Palestinian sources in the occupied territories have said 
that the Israeli army had arrested more than 500 militants in a 
bid to destroy the group after it launched attacks which claimed 
the lives of 14 Israelis this month. 
  The mass roundup "comes at a time when the enemy government 
prepares to release thousands of prisoners who don't belong to 
Hamas in a bid to divide the Palestinian people," the statement 
said. 
  Israel is to set free around 5,000 prisoners after the 
signing of a final deal to launch delayed Palestinian autonomy 
in the Gaza Strip and West Bank town of Jericho, which may take 
place in May. 
  Israeli negotiators have rejected requests to set free 
members of Islamic militant groups opposed to peace. 
  Hamas called on the London-based human rights group Amnesty 
International "to pressure the Israeli government into freeing 
immediately the prisoners." 

</TEXT>

