<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-079 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on Rabin, Peres Differences </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    More on Rabin, Peres Differences </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2404123994 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1200 GMT 24 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2404123994 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Differences of opinion between Prime Minister 
Yitzhaq Rabin and Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres over 
negotiations with the Palestinians are centered on whether 
Israel must sign the agreement within two weeks. Our 
correspondent Hayim Hecht reports that Minister Peres in his 
talks with Yasir 'Arafat in Romania received the impression that 
if the agreement is not signed within two weeks, then, in his 
words, the whole thing will be a dead letter. Mr. Peres 
believes that the detailed negotiations on security should be 
finalized, the agreement signed, and the remaining issues worked 
out later. Mr. Rabin, on the other hand, believes that before 
the agreement is signed, issues touching on sovereignty, such as 
currency, stamps, and telephone dialing areas, should also be 
worked out. 
  Environment Minister Yosi Sarid said there is no dispute 
between Rabin and Peres. Minister Tzaban said the differences 
refer to the niceties, and Police Minister Shahal believes that 
the issue is a matter of different perspectives. He believes 
the full cabinet must be involved in the deliberations. Under 
the draft agreement Peres brought back from Romania, there will 
be a Peres-'Arafat meeting in Cairo on Thursday [28 April] in 
order to prepare a meeting between the Prime Minister Rabin and 
'Arafat next week. The only issues which will remain unresolved 
at the Rabin-'Arafat will be the size of the Jericho area and 
the location of the Palestinian policeman deployed on the Jordan 
River bridge. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

