<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Golan Settlers, Opposition Reject Rabin Remarks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Golan Settlers, Opposition Reject Rabin Remarks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2104124694 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1200 GMT 21 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2104124694 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sharp reactions to Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin's 
remarks concerning his willingness to remove Golan settlements 
for the sake of peace have been voiced in the Golan settlements 
and the political establishment. The Golan Heights Settlements 
Committee says the remarks undermine the existence of all the 
settlements in the north and raise a question about the 
country's future. 
  Likud Chairman Binyamin Netanyahu says Rabin's remarks 
attest 
to the total political collapse of a weak prime minister. Rabin 
disavows his commitment to the settlements' continued existence 
and the control of the Golan in the peace era as well, Knesset 
Member [MK] Netanyahu says. 
  The Tzomet faction is demanding that the prime minister 
announce immediate elections in order to allow the people to 
decide whether Golan settlements should be removed. MK Refa'el 
Eytan says that Rabin has apparently been lying to the nation 
for a long time. 
  The National Religious Party says the prime minister is 
forfeiting the Jewish people's assets like a political greenhorn. 

</TEXT>

