<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Husayn-Christopher London Meeting Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Husayn-Christopher London Meeting Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2504065894 Amman SAWT AL-SHA'B in Arabic 25 Apr 94 pp 1, 20 </F>
<F P=103> JN2504065894 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman SAWT AL-SHA'B </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "Husayn-Christopher Meeting and the Sought </F>
Success"] 
  [Text] There are positive signs in the American position 
indicating that the scheduled meeting between His Majesty King 
Husayn and U.S. Secretary of State Christopher will be a success. 
  The recent statements by President Clinton and Christopher 
on 
the cordial relations between Jordan and Washington and the 
siege of al-'Aqabah show that the U.S. Administration 
understands, or almost understands, the great damage inflicted 
by the embargo on Jordan's economy and trade. 
  Furthermore, there is remarkable U.S. interest in activating 
the peace process and ending the crises on all tracks. 
  We hope the U.S. secretary will bring something new 
regarding 
the U.S. stand vis-a-vis the siege imposed on Jordan. The 
lifting of the siege would rejuvenate Jordanian enthusiasm on 
role its in the peace process, particularly if Israel agrees to 
discuss all unresolved issues, such as water, borders, refugees, 
and Jerusalem. 
  The important thing is to see the U.S. Administration end 
its 
bias toward Israel and work to force Israel to hold negotiations 
based on withdrawal from all occupied Arab territory in 
accordance with Security Council Resolutions 242, 338, and 425 
and the land for peace formula. 
  The success of the Husayn-Christopher meeting in London 
today 
will be an important indicator of U.S. interest in activating 
the peace process and rendering it a success on all tracks. 
During his meeting with the U.S. secretary today, King Husayn 
will speak in the name of all cordon states and will reiterate 
the principles of the Arab position with regard to the 
Jordanian, Syrian, and Lebanese tracks on the basis of the 
resolutions of international legitimacy. 
  We hope Secretary Christopher will respond to this position. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

