<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   French Embassy `Sources' on al-'Aqabah Blockade </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    French Embassy `Sources' on al-'Aqabah Blockade </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2404082694 Amman AL-DUSTUR in Arabic 24 Apr 94 pp 1, 20 </F>
<F P=103> JN2404082694 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-DUSTUR </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Hamdan al-Hajj] </F>
  [Text] Sources at the French Embassy in Amman reiterated 
France's position, which supports and understands the Jordanian 
proposals on stopping naval inspections off the Port of 
al-'Aqabah and moving the inspections into the port while 
maintaining the effectiveness of trade sanctions imposed on Iraq. 
  In an exclusive statement to AL-DUSTUR, these sources said 
France supports in principle inspections on land, saying this 
will ease the economic burden on Jordan caused by ship 
inspections in the Red Sea. 
  These sources called for expediting measures to end the 
restrictions imposed on free navigation into the Port of 
al-'Aqabah, and pointed out His Majesty King Husayn's position 
on this subject, which calls for lifting and easing these 
measures before Jordan returns to the negotiations table. 
  The sources emphasized that France has held several contacts 
with Jordan on this issue in its capacity as a country directly 
concerned in this subject, in addition to contacts France has 
conducted with European countries and the United States in order 
to reach an agreement on the ideal way to carry out inspections 
and ease the burden on Jordan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

