<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   BABIL Article Says U.S. New World Order `Cannot Last' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    BABIL Article Says U.S. New World Order `Cannot Last' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2404101494 Baghdad INA in Arabic 0755 GMT 24 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN2404101494 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad INA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Baghdad, 24 Apr (INA) -- An Iraqi political writer 
has said that the new world order adopted by the United States 
cannot last. 
  In an article published in BABIL today, Amir al-Hilu cast 
doubt about the ability of the United States to continue its 
hegemony as the sole international power that wants to control 
the world's resources after the disintegration of the Soviet 
Union and the socialist bloc states. 
  He emphasized that the world cannot be run by a single power 
because this conflicts with the interests of countries, whether 
on their national level, or the level of the international blocs. 
  He said the negative impact of the U.S. policy of hegemony 
and undisputed domination has become clear. This policy, which 
depends on the logic of force, has a negative impact on the 
interests of other countries, as demonstrated in its domination 
of the United Nations and the Security Council and the adoption 
of resolutions that serve the U.S. politician without any 
considerations for the interests of other countries. This has 
happened and is happening now, represented in its insistence on 
maintaining the siege against Iraq, the threat to use force 
against Japan, and the intervention in Somali affairs. 
  The article emphasized that political and economic 
developments in today's world, which the U.S. Administration 
said will be stable and secure under the umbrella of its new 
world order, reflect the falseness of these claims because it is 
a chaotic world in which wars and military interventions prevail. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

