<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sha'th, Shahaq Note Progress in Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sha'th, Shahaq Note Progress in Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2204202794 Algiers Voice of Palestine in Arabic 1702 GMT 
22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2204202794 </F>
<F P=104>  Algiers Voice of Palestine </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Dr. Nabil Sha'th and General Amnon Shahaq, the 
heads of the Palestinian and Israeli negotiating delegations, 
have both agreed that progress has been made in the round of 
talks which was concluded in Cairo yesterday. Dr. Sha'th said 
that this round has achieved considerable progress despite the 
difficulty it faced in the beginning. Meanwhile Shahaq said 
that the round was positive and fruitful and that the two sides 
were very close to signing an agreement on the implementation of 
self-rule in Gaza and Jericho. 
  At their news conferences, they said that the new round 
which 
is to start next Sunday will be that last. While Nabil Sha'th 
expects a final agreement to be signed between 2 and 5 May by 
the Palestinian president, brother Abu Ammar [Yasir 'Arafat], 
and Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin, General Shahaq was 
more reserved and did not give a date for the signing. [passage 
omitted] 
  Shahaq said that the two sides are awaiting the results of 
the meetings of the economic committee in Paris to include them 
in the resolutions which have been finalized in order to reach a 
general agreement. [passage omitted] 
  Meanwhile the heads of the Palestinian and Israeli 
delegations to the economic talks in Paris have decided to hold 
consultations with their presidents because of the obstacles 
which they cannot overcome through negotiations. Sources in the 
two delegations said that Avraham Shohat, Israeli finance 
minister and head of the Israeli delegation to the economic 
talks, has indeed left Paris this morning for Israel. The 
official spokesman of the Israeli delegation, Eric Gordan, said 
that Shohat will attend next Sunday's Israeli cabinet meeting. 
  Meanwhile, Samir Hulaylah, member of the Israeli delegation, 
said that brother Abu-al-'Ala', director of the PLO's Economic 
Department, will also leave Paris for Tunis where he is to brief 
the PLO leadership on the progress of the economic talks. 
  Shohat and Abu-al-'Ala' are expected to return to Paris on 
Monday afternoon. 
  The two delegations could not reach an agreement on customs 
policy and on matters regarding Palestinian manpower. 

</TEXT>

