<F P=100> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Judicial Sources' on Iraqi Diplomats `Fully' Confessing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Judicial Sources' on Iraqi Diplomats `Fully' Confessing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2304110394 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1010 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2304110394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beirut, 23 Apr (MENA)--Lebanese judicial sources 
today stated that during the preliminary interrogation 
yesterday, Iraqi diplomat Deputy Consul 'Ali Sultan Darwish and 
chief of embassy guards Hadi Hasan confessed fully to the 
assassination of Iraqi opposition member Talib Suhayl al-Tamimi 
in his home in Beirut. 
  The sources said that during the 12-hour interrogation 
yesterday, Hadi Hasan gave a full confession on how the crime 
was planned in coordination with Muhammad Faris Kadhim, chief of 
intelligence at the Iraqi embassy, and defendants Khalid Khalaf, 
'Ali Sultan Darwish, and George Tarjian. 
  According to Hasan, Kadhim had asked him to assassinate 
al-Tamimi at the orders of the Iraqi intelligence in Baghdad, 
after furnishing him with the crime weapon. 
  The sources note that defendant 'Ali Sultan Darwish 
confessed 
to planning and preparing to carry out the crime with his 
colleagues and to hiding weapons, particularly the murder weapon. 
  Darwish said that the Iraqi intelligence in Baghdad had 
issued orders to assassinate al-Tamimi at once as an opponent of 
Saddam Husayn's regime. He confessed to committing the crime 
with his colleagues. 
  The investigating judge has ordered the extension of the 
defendants' remand in solitary confinement, and prevented 
visitors. The number of persons implicated in the case has thus 
risen to five, including three diplomats. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-13916 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes079_n_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-079 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ba'th Leader Condemns Breaking Ties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ba'th Leader Condemns Breaking Ties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2304102794 Baghdad INA in Arabic 0935 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN2304102794 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad INA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Nicosia, 23 Apr (INA)--Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid al-Rafi'i, 
secretary of the Lebanon Command of the Arab Socialist Ba'th 
Party and former member of the Lebanese Chamber of Deputies, has 
condemned the Lebanese Government's decision to sever diplomatic 
ties with Iraq, describing it as a decision that is lacking in 
patriotic and pan-Arab sentiments, as well as any legal or 
legitimate grounds. 
  In statements carried by Arab and foreign media 
organizations 
in Nicosia, Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid al-Rafi'i asserted that the 
Lebanese people cannot but be supportive of Iraq, which has 
strongly nurtured their struggle in the course of their defense 
of their national unity and promoted their steadfastness on 
their national soil to enable them to liberate it from the filth 
of the Zionist enemy. 
  Al-Rafi'i noted that the Lebanese Government's decision to 
sever ties with Iraq is part of a conspiratorial scenario 
targeting both Iraq and Lebanon. 
  Al-Rafi'i urged the nationalist and pan-Arab forces that are 
opposed to the subjugation of the Lebanese political 
decisionmaking process to close their ranks and overlook their 
differences to save Lebanon from the current state of loss and 
thwart the schemes that aim to eliminate its sovereignty. 
  Al-Rafi'i also condemned the campaign of arrests targeting 
nationalist and pan-Arab figures in Lebanon, which is coupled 
with another campaign aimed to muzzle intellectual freedom and 
heavily censor various Lebanese media organizations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

