<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Irish Defense Minister Holds Talks With Officials </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Irish Defense Minister Holds Talks With Officials </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Nateq-Nuri, Velayati Meet Minister </H4>

<F P=102> LD2504142294 Tehran IRNA in English 1315 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2504142294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, April 25, IRNA -- Visiting Irish Minister of 
Defence and Marine Affairs David Andrews here Monday [25 April] 
expressed his country's readiness for promotion of scientific 
and economic cooperation with Iran particularly in fishery 
industry. Meeting with Majlis Speaker Hojjat ol-Eslam 'Ali 
Akbar Nateq-Nuri, Andrews invited the speaker, on behalf of his 
Irish counterpart to pay an official visit to Dublin soon. 
  Andrews said both countries had successful cooperation in 
fields of fishing and manufacturing fishing equipment, hoping 
that Iran could use Ireland's technical expertise by despatching 
students at different educational levels to Ireland. 
  Nateq-Nuri in return said Iran was prepared to exchange 
expertise with Ireland in forestry, fishery, jetty and ship 
construction industry. He also expressed hope that he could 
visit Ireland at a proper time. 
  As for massacre of Muslims in Bosnia-Herzegovina Nateq-Nuri 
denounced the dual approach of the U.N. Security Council to the 
plight of Bosnian Muslims and once again called for lifting of 
arms embargo against Bosnia. 
  Commenting on Gaza-Jericho compromise deal, the speaker 
called it an unjust agreement seeking to stabilize the 
aggressors in the occupied lands. 
  Meanwhile Andrews discussed issues of mutual interest with 
Foreign Minister 'Ali Akbar Velayati today and called for 
further expansion of Tehran-Dublin ties in all domains. 
  Velayati in return referring to the ample grounds for 
Tehran-Dublin cooperation welcomed promotion of bilateral 
relations. 

</TEXT>

